The Wall Street Journal

         Spectrum Brands appoints Andreas Rouve as CEO
    








    By
        
        Angela Chen

Published: Mar 16, 2015 7:32 a.m. ET

Share






















































 



 




















By

                                        AngelaChen







Spectrum Brands Holdings Inc. has appointed Andreas Rouve as chief executive, succeeding Dave Lumley, who is retiring.  Rouve, 53 years old, was most recently chief operating officer of the consumer goods company, whose diverse offerings of consumer products range from Rayovac batteries to George Foreman grills. He also held positions as president of the company’s international division, and senior vice president of the European battery segment. Previously, Rouve worked at Varta AG, a German company that produces batteries for the industrial market.  “Andreas has provided outstanding operating and financial leadership as COO and previously in key international and European executive roles over the years,” said Lumley, 60.  Lumley had announced his plans to retire in January, noting that the company would enter a transition-services employment agreement that would extend to Sept. 30, the end of Spectrum Brands’ 

                            
                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                  
                                    SPB, -0.70%

                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                          fiscal year. He will remain on the company’s board.  These moves come as, late last year, Spectrum Brands named Douglas L. Martin, a former Newell Rubbermaid executive, its chief financial officer.   An expanded version of this report appears at WSJ.com.  


