Andreas Rouvé 
































































AP

CORPORATE LEADERSHIP | 13-YEAR EMPLOYEE TO REPLACE RETIREE
        
        Spectrum Brands promotes COO Andreas Rouvé to CEO
    


BOB VAN ENKENVOORT 
bvanenkenvoort@madison.com, 608-252-6155

Mar 16, 2015










































Andreas Rouvé































































Spectrum Brands Holdings has a new CEO, and the company didn’t have to look far to find him.Andreas Rouvé, 53, who started with Spectrum in 2002, will assume his new role on April 1. The Middleton-based company announced the appointment Monday.Rouvé will succeed Dave Lumley, 60, who recently announced plans to retire.
Rouvé was named chief operating officer in February 2014.Prior to that, Rouvé was president of the company’s international operations for 13 months. He served as senior vice president and managing director of Spectrum Brands’ European battery and personal care business from 2007 to 2013.During that time, he led the integration of the home appliances and pet supplies European businesses in 2010-2011.He joined Spectrum Brands in 2002 as chief financial officer of the European battery division.“Andreas is an impressive business leader and has been a tremendous contributor to our growth and success through the years,” said David Maura, Spectrum Brands chairman of the board, in a news release. “Andreas is well-suited to lead our company to the next level as we follow the same vision, strategy and direction that have served us so well to date.”Previously, Rouvé worked 13 years with VARTA AG in a variety of top management positions. He holds a master’s degree in business administration from the University of Mannheim in Germany and a doctorate in economics and social science from the University of Linz in Austria.Lumley will remain on the company’s board of directors after his retirement. He joined the company at the start of 2006 and has served as president and CEO since April 2010.Spectrum’s brands include Rayovac batteries, Remington shavers, George Foreman grills, Cutter insect repellent and Dingo pet food products.
The company announced in January that it bought Salix Animal Health of Deerfield Beach, Florida, a maker of natural rawhide dog chews.Since 2009, the company has also added:Small appliance maker Russell Hobbs;
Black Flag and TAT insecticides;FURminator pet products;Stanley Black & Decker’s hardware and home improvement division, which included the residential lockset business of Tong Lung Metal Industry Co., Taiwan;A majority share of Shaser Bioscience skin care products;Tell Manufacturing door locks;Liquid Fence animal repellent;Iams and Eukanuba European pet food brands.













Angry


0


Sad


0


Funny


0


Wow


0


Love


0































































        

        
        Spectrum Brands CEO Dave Lumley plans to retire this year


Lumley, who joined the company at the start of 2006 and has served as president and CEO since April 2010, will leave once the consumer products company he has overseen for nearly five years finds his replacement.





















        

        
        Spectrum Brands buys another pet products company


The Middleton consumer products company is adding Salix Animal Health, of Florida, to the fold.













        

        
        Spectrum Brands reports lower earnings


The Middleton company reported results for its first fiscal quarter of 2015.













        

        
        Spectrum Brands' profits rise


But the Middleton company's stock dipped in trading Thursday.













        

        
        Spectrum Brands acquires Iams, Eukanuba pet food brands in Europe


Middleton-based Spectrum Brands Holdings announced Tuesday morning that it has acquired two pet food brands in Europe from Procter & Gamble, expanding its scope in the pet products industry.













        

        
        Spectrum Brands signs deal to acquire Tell Manufacturing


Lancaster, Pennsylvania-based Tell is a privately held maker and distributor of commercial doors, locks and hardware with annual revenues of nearly $40 million.













        

        
        Spectrum Brands stock soars, and so do CEO Dave Lumley's gains


The stock price for the Madison company has risen about 50 percent over the past year.





















        

        
        Spectrum Brands moves to Middleton


The consumer products company is leaving the West Side location where it's had facilities for nearly 50 years.



















Andreas Rouvé









        

        
        Spectrum Brands will buy Armored AutoGroup for $1.4 billion


The purchase will add car care products to the Middleton company's growing list of consumer goods.











        

        
        Spectrum Brands earnings dip in second fiscal quarter


But the Middleton company's stock still climbed Wednesday.



















        

        
        Spectrum Brands earnings dip


The Middleton company includes Rayovac batteries and STP motor oil.



















        

        
        Spectrum Brands names new exec chairman, with high level pay package


Meanwhile, the former CEO and EVP left in 2015 with golden parachutes of nearly $12 million each.


















